[2] United Kingdom (West Midlands)
Date: Wed 2 May 2018
Source: Solihull Observer [edited]
https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/doctors-warn-outbreak-of-measles-spreading-through-west-midlands-6169/


An outbreak of measles originating in Solihull has spread to other areas of the West Midlands prompting an urgent vaccination appeal.

Public Health England (PHE) has issued a warning to parents of children under 5 years old who have missed their measles vaccinations.

Health experts are working with local councils and NHS partners to make sure anyone who needs a vaccination is aware of their importance.

Families will receive a reminder letter from NHS [National Health Service] England (West Midlands) and PHE West Midlands this week [week of Sun 29 Apr 2018] , asking them to arrange immunisation at their GP surgery.

At the same time, PHE has written to all West Midlands GPs asking them to be on the alert for the symptoms of measles and to take the opportunity to immunise children and adults who may not have received 2 doses of the MMR (measles) vaccine.

The call comes as the outbreak, which originally focused in Birmingham and Solihull, has now become a West Midlands wide community issue with over 100 cases.

Dr Bharat Sibal, PHE West Midlands lead consultant in communicable disease control, said: "Those affected are all recovering, but it's important to understand measles can be a very serious illness and lead to severe complications, especially in people who are particularly vulnerable or have other health conditions.

"The current outbreak in the West Midlands has seen 51 per cent of cases admitted to hospital. ...

"The ages of people affected ranges from 3 months -- 50 years, however the average age is 5 years - which is why it's particularly important for parents to have their children vaccinated when offered. ...-more

[Byline: Felix Nobes]

